description.narrative: (Pakistan): The Agribusiness Project provides technical assistance to farmers, farmer enterprise groups, and processors to increase Pakistan's on-farm productivity and competitiveness, enabling them to produce more high quality food for domestic markets. The project will build on its prior year efforts organizing farmer enterprise groups by connecting them with larger agribusiness enterprises and markets.After a restructuring exercise in 2013, the project has now adopted a more targeted approach, focusing on profitability, sustainability, and transformation in eight value chains, namely apricot (in~Gilgit-Baltistan), banana (Sindh), chili (Sindh), citrus (Punjab), high value off-season vegetables (Khyber Pakhtunkhwa [or KP], FATA, Punjab, and Sindh), livestock and meat (Punjab), seed potato (Gligit-Baltistan and KP), and grape (the Potohar region around Islamabad).~The project will work in clusters, which will become models to be followed by others around them.With FY2014 funding the project will expand and solidify efforts during the final year of implementation.~The project will provide technical assistance to farmer enterprise groups to improve the quality and quantity of their produce as well as adding value to products through improved post-harvest handling, grading, and sorting.~Such efforts will increase farm-level income and create new on-farm employment opportunities. The project will also work with partners' businesses to assist them in expanding their capacity and market access by promoting new investments in modern technologies.~This will happen through cost-sharing grants, providing business development services to entrepreneurs in agribusinesses, and assisting in the promotion of Pakistani products in regional export markets through the participation in trade shows and other missions.
